Estimate parameters and their covariance from a set of estimating equations

M-estimation theory provides a framework for asympotic properties of estimators that are solutions to estimating equations. Many R packages implement specific applications of estimating equations. geex aims to be provide a more general framework that any modelling method can use to compute point and variance estimates for parameters that are solutions to estimating equations of the form: $$\sum_i \psi(O_i, \hat{\theta}) = 0$$

estimate_equations(eeFUN, data, units = NULL, weights = NULL,
  roots = NULL, outer_eeargs = NULL, inner_eeargs = NULL,
  compute_roots = TRUE, compute_vcov = TRUE, corrections_list = NULL,
  derivFUN = numDeriv::jacobian, derivFUN_control = list(method =
  "Richardson"), rootFUN = rootSolve::multiroot, rootFUN_control = NULL,
  rootFUN_object = "root", approxFUN = NULL, approxFUN_control = NULL)

Arguments

eeFUN

a function that takes in group-level data and returns a function that takes parameters as its first argument
data

a data.frame
units

an optional character string identifying the grouping variable in data
roots

a vector of parameter estimates must be provided if compute_roots = FALSE
outer_eeargs

a list of arguments passed to the outer (data) function of eeFUN. (optional)
inner_eeargs

a list of arguments passed to the inner (theta) function of eeFUN. (optional)
compute_roots

whether or not to find the roots of the estimating equations. Defaults to TRUE.
compute_vcov

whether or not to compute the variance-covariance matrix. Defaults to TRUE.
corrections_list

an optional list of small sample corrections where each list element is a list with two elements: correctFUN and correctFUN_options. See details.
derivFUN

the function used to take derivatives of the estimating equation functions. Defaults to jacobian.
derivFUN_control

a list of options passed to jacobian (or the derivFUN function).
rootFUN

the function used to find roots of the estimating equations. Defaults to multiroot.
rootFUN_control

a list of options to be passed to the rootsolver function
approxFUN

a function that approximates the inner function of eeFUN. (EXPERIMENTAL).
approxFUN_control

arguments passed to approxFUN

Value

a list with the following

  • parameters - a vector of estimated parameters

  • vcov - the variance-covariance matrix for the parameters

  • corrections - a list of corrected variance-covariance matrices

Details

The basic idea of geex is for the analyst to provide at least two items:

  • data

  • eeFUN: (the \(\psi\) function), a function that takes unit-level data and returns a function in terms of parameters (\(\theta\))

With the eeFUN, geex computes the roots of the estimating equations and/or the empirical sandwich variance estimator.

The root finding algorithm defaults to multiroot to estimate roots though the solver algorithm can be specified in the rootFUN argument. Starting values for multiroot are passed via the rootFUN_control argument. See NA for information on customizing the root solver function.

To compute only the covariance matrix, set compute_roots = FALSE and pass estimates of \(\theta\) via the roots argument.

M-estimation is often used for clustered data, and a variable by which to split the data.frame into independent units is specified by the units argument. This argument defaults to NULL, in which case the number of units equals the number of rows in the data.frame.

For information on the finite-sample corrections, refer to the finite sample correction API vignette: NA

Writing an eeFUN

Description

An eeFUN is a function that takes in *unit* level data plus possible "outer" arguments (see section on eefUN argument) and returns a function whose first argument is theta. See the examples below or the package vignettes for more information.

Additional arguments

Additional arguments may be passed to both the inner and outer function of the eeFUN. Elements in an outer_eeargs list are passed to the outer function; any elements of the inner_eeargs list are passed to the inner function. For an example, see the finite sample correction vignette [NA].

References

Stefanski, L. A., & Boos, D. D. (2002). The calculus of M-estimation. The American Statistician, 56(1), 29-38.

    c(Y1 - theta[1],
     (Y1 - theta[1])^2 - theta[2] ))
}}

# A simple linear model for regressing X1 and X2 on Y4
lm_eefun <- function(data){
 X <- cbind(1, data$X1, data$X2)
 Y <- data$Y4
  function(theta){
    t(X) %*% (Y - X %*% theta)
   }
 }

estimate_equations(
 eeFUN = lm_eefun,
 data  = geexex,
